This issue is very similar to #14623, but can be solved independently. 

Currently it's impossible for the `SIODelegate` to distinguish if the client has sent a plain string or a serialized (JSON) object.

As a example I'm sending this with the official JS client:

``` js
socket.emit('test-str', 'string');
socket.emit('test-obj', {type: 'obj'});
```

And with a delegate like:

``` c++
void ServerImpl::fireEventToScript(cocos2d::network::SIOClient* _client, const std::string& event, const std::string& data)
{
    CCLOG("GOT %s %s", event.c_str(), data.c_str());
}
```

The log will contain:

```
GOT test-str "string"
GOT test-obj {"type":"obj"}
```

A possible solution for this could be to add another parameter to `fireEventToScript` indicating that `data` contains a serialized JSON object:

``` c++
void ServerImpl::fireEventToScript(cocos2d::network::SIOClient* _client, const std::string& event, const std::string& data, const bool containsJson)
{
    if (containsJson) {
        // I know that I might use rapidjson here
    } else {
        // It's not safe to use rapidjson on data
    }
}
```

**NOTE**: As soon as we implement #14619, we should support JSON objects there too!

As [described here](http://socket.io/docs/server-api/#server%28opts:object%29), the official SocketIO JS client is able to connect to a custom path on the server. It would be awesome if the cocos2dx native implementation of SocketIO would do the same and we could get a comparable behaviour between native and JS.

A possible API could look something like:

``` c++
auto client = cocos2d::network::SocketIO::connect(someUri, someDelegate, '/my/path');
```

For a server like:

``` js
var io = require('socket.io')(80, { path: '/my/path' });
io.on('connection', function (socket) {
    // The SocketIO handshake will now be available on
    //     http://localhost:80/my/path/socket.io/...
    // instead of 
    //     http://localhost:80/socket.io/...
});
```

**NOTE:** It's important to distinguish between `path` and `namespace`! A `namespace` is used to multiplex different scopes over one connection. But the `path` option is important for everyone hosting the socketIO server on a different endpoint location, as it's not always possible to use `/socket.io/..` on the server root.

As [described here](http://socket.io/docs/#sending-and-getting-data-%28acknowledgements%29) SocketIO supports custom acknowledgements. It would be awesome if the cocos2dx native implementation of SocketIO would do the same and we could get a comparable behaviour between native and JS.

A possible API could look something like this:

``` c++
auto client = cocos2d::network::SocketIO::connect(someUri, someDelegate);
client->emit("ferret", "tobi", [](const std::string& data) {
    CCLOG("%s", data.c_str());
});
```

For a server that does something like:

``` js
var io = require('socket.io')(80);
io.on('connection', function (socket) {
    socket.on('ferret', function (name, fn) {
        fn('woot');
    });
});
```

**NOTE**: A ack can be issued from both sides - the client **and** the server. In the example above we only request a ack from the server (`client->emit()`) but we should support responding to a ack request as well (`SIODelegate:: fireEventToScript`). Please have a look [at this example](https://gist.github.com/michaelcontento/b1b9d7cf18b8c30f6bad) that illustrates custom ack with the official JS client.

```
        PageView* page = PageView::create();
        page->setBackGroundColorType(Layout::BackGroundColorType::SOLID);
        page->setBackGroundColor(ccc3(100, 100, 0));
        page->setSize(Size(300,300));

        Layout* child = Layout::create();
        child->setBackGroundColorType(Layout::BackGroundColorType::SOLID);
        child->setBackGroundColor(ccc3(0, 100, 100));
        page->addChild(child);

        page->forceDoLayout();
```

